{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017e1MBJ1Drb6jgmmFQXscia","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Test count went from 145 to 146, confirming our new test was picked up and ran (and passed as \"skipped\" since the server wasn't running). \n\nWait, 146 passing (not skipped). The integration test skips itself when server is not available using `return` inside the test rather than `skip()`, so Vitest would count it as \"passed\" (the test ran, checked `!serverAvailable`, and returned early). That's expected.\n\nNow let me write the evaluation file.\n\nKey findings:\n1. Phase A (fast checks): ALL PASS\n   - All test suites passing (146 tests), linting clean, type checking passes, build succeeds, exports are correct, and test cases cover the breakdown functionality ✅\n\n2. Phase B (slow checks): FAIL\n   - The HTTP endpoint for trends is returning a 500 error instead of 200, which points to a bug in the `buildTrendsQuery` function that's generating ISO timestamps in a format ClickHouse DateTime64 doesn't accept\n   - The issue is in how timestamps are being constructed—I need to switch from ISO format to space-separated format and update the `computeEndExclusive` function to match\n   - I've added an integration test case to catch this at runtime, but the core issue is critical since it breaks all trends queries in production despite passing static checks\n\nThe score is really a 5/10 because while the implementation passes linting, type checking, and build steps, the actual query functionality fails when it hits the database. A single targeted fix to the timestamp formatting in `buildTrendsQuery` would resolve it.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":370,"cache_read_input_tokens":73320,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":370},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"st